nsportation0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book introduces the powerful and provocative new fiction and poetry of Israel's women writers to an English-speaking audience. Read together, the stories and poems in this book will help to create a more sophisticated understanding of Middle Eastern passions and realities, and will foster a wealth of discussion about the meanings of homeland, exile, and diaspora; women's sexuality and spirituality; gender roles; the legacy of the Holocaust; the tensions and reconciliations of religion and secular life; the effects of war; and the power of memory.In her introduction, Miriyam Glazer vividly reconstructs the diversities, tensions, and complexity of current Israeli literature, and the book reflects the multiculturality of modern-day Israel by including stories and poems originally written in Arabic, Russian, Hebrew, and English. Brief biographical and critical introductions are provided for each writer, and the book features specially commissioned and new translations of twenty stories and seventy-five poems, many available here for the first time in English.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aIsraeli literaturexWomen authorsvTranslations into English. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 4aGeneral Interest : Poetry. 4aJewish Studies : Jewish Studies. 4aLiterature : Hebrew Language and Literature. 7aPOETRY / Anthologies (multiple authors).2bisacsh1 aAini, Leah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlkalay-Gut, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmir, Devorah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBack, Rachel Tzvia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBe